==English==

===Etymology===
From Latin '''[[castellum]]''', literally ''little camp'', from '''[[castrum]]''', ''camp'', from '''[[casa]]''', ''hut'' or ''cottage''

===Pronunciation===
*käs'(ə)l, /ˈkɑːs(ə)l/, /<tt>"kA:s(@)l</tt>/
*:[[Rhymes:English:-ɑːs(ə)l|Rhymes: -ɑːs(ə)l]]
*kăs'(ə)l, /ˈkæs(ə)l/, /<tt>"kæs(@)l</tt>/
*:[[Rhymes:English:-æs(ə)l|Rhymes: -æs(ə)l]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A large building that is [[fortified]] and contains many [[defence]]s; in previous ages often inhabited by a [[nobleman]] or [[king]].
# A [[chess]] piece shaped like a castle [[tower]] which is also called a [[rook]].
# A [[close helmet]].
#:'''Quotations'''
#:*'''1786''', The castle was perhaps a figurative name for a close headpiece deduced from it's enclosing and defending the head, as a castle did the whole body; or a corruption from the Old French word Casquetel, a small or light helmet. &mdash; Francis Grose, ''A Treatise on Ancient Armour and Weapons'', page 12.
{{wikipedia}}

===Usage notes===
For the chess piece, chess players prefer the term [[rook]].

===Synonyms===
*(1): [[fortress]], [[keep]]
*(2): [[rook]]

